**List**

You can format a header by using "#" followed by the header text, and a list by using "*" followed by the list item. You can also use "-" instead of "*" for a bullet point.

Here is a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing Markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text:
```cpp
#include <string>
#include <boost/algorithm/string/replace.hpp>
#include <cctype>

std::string convertMarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Replace Markdown headers with HTML headers
    for (char& c : markdown) {
        if (c == '#') {
            html += "<h1>";
            break;
        } else if (c == ' ') {
            html += "&nbsp;";
        } else {
            html += c;
        }
    }

    // Replace Markdown lists with HTML lists
    std::string listItem = "";
    for (const char* p = markdown.c_str(); *p != '\0'; p++) {
        if (*p == '*') {
            if (!listItem.empty()) {
                html += "</li>";
            }
            html += "<li>";
            listItem = "";
        } else if (*p == ' ') {
            listItem += " ";
        } else {
            listItem += *p;
        }
    }
    if (!listItem.empty()) {
        html += "</li>";
    }

    return html;
}
```
This function uses a simple state machine to parse the Markdown input and generate HTML output. It replaces Markdown headers with HTML headers, and Markdown lists with HTML lists. Note that this implementation is very basic and does not handle all possible Markdown syntax.

You can use this function like this:
```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdown = "We have the following items on sale:\n"
        "* Wristwatch - $199\n"
        "* Shoes - $299\n"
        "* Coat - $499\n"
        "\n"
        "You can format a header by using '#' followed by the header text, and a list by using '*' followed by the list item. You can also use '-' instead of '*' for a bullet point.";
    std::string html = convertMarkdownToHTML(markdown);

    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```
